1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:02,240
- Even if they wanna cut
down, even if they know

2
00:00:02,241 --> 00:00:04,600
it's killing them, they
find they can't stop.

3
00:00:05,480 --> 00:00:06,880
- My name's Chris Van Tulleken.

4
00:00:06,881 --> 00:00:09,440
I'm an NHS doctor, I'm a scientist,

5
00:00:09,441 --> 00:00:12,920
and I'm part of a growing
group of doctors and academics

6
00:00:12,921 --> 00:00:15,520
who are increasingly
worried about the effect

7
00:00:15,521 --> 00:00:19,080
that the global food
system is having on all of us.

8
00:00:19,081 --> 00:00:20,659
When it comes to
obesity, the way that we've

9
00:00:20,660 --> 00:00:24,040
understood the problem
is it's a failure of willpower.

10
00:00:24,041 --> 00:00:26,720
People are just making bad choices.

11
00:00:26,721 --> 00:00:28,240
They're somewhat lazy.

12
00:00:28,241 --> 00:00:30,240
It's basically their fault.

13
00:00:30,241 --> 00:00:33,600
This is American government data for
men and women of all different ages,

14
00:00:33,601 --> 00:00:36,320
the different lines of
different ages, for obesity.

15
00:00:36,321 --> 00:00:40,258
What you see is between
1960 and 1975, there's a

16
00:00:40,259 --> 00:00:43,400
fairly steady percentage
of obesity in the population.

17
00:00:44,320 --> 00:00:49,920
But in the mid-1970s, obesity starts going
up in all of the groups simultaneously.

18
00:00:52,440 --> 00:00:54,880
Now, if you're saying
willpower is responsible,

19
00:00:54,881 --> 00:00:57,291
what you're proposing
is that all of these groups

20
00:00:57,292 --> 00:01:00,880
of people simultaneously
lost moral responsibility.

21
00:01:00,881 --> 00:01:02,840
And that's not plausible.

22
00:01:02,841 --> 00:01:05,912
Something else happened
to our food in the

23
00:01:05,913 --> 00:01:09,240
mid-1970s to make it
irresistible to people.

24
00:01:09,241 --> 00:01:11,960
My name's John Ruff,
and I've spent 40 years

25
00:01:11,961 --> 00:01:15,640
in the food industry across
seven different countries.

26
00:01:15,641 --> 00:01:18,747
Companies spend a lot of
time optimising all aspects

27
00:01:18,748 --> 00:01:22,440
of their product, the
flavour, the taste, the texture.

28
00:01:22,441 --> 00:01:24,040
People want their product to be as good,

29
00:01:24,041 --> 00:01:27,520
if not better, than the
competitor, so it will sell more.

30
00:01:27,521 --> 00:01:31,000
We use trained sensory
panels to give us ratings.

31
00:01:31,001 --> 00:01:34,560
Is it squishy, is it hard,
is it soft, is it crunchy?

32
00:01:34,561 --> 00:01:38,360
That's very much how
the food industry operates.

33
00:01:38,361 --> 00:01:41,336
One thing many people
don't realise is that factory

34
00:01:41,337 --> 00:01:44,840
processing changes the
textural properties of food.

35
00:01:44,841 --> 00:01:49,000
An interesting fact about soft food
is you're not chewing it as much.

36
00:01:49,001 --> 00:01:52,600
That actually short-circuits
the normal satiety mechanisms

37
00:01:52,601 --> 00:01:55,960
that you would have if you were
actually chewing food properly.

38
00:01:55,961 --> 00:01:59,680
So you're bypassing the normal
mechanism that tells you that you're full.

39
00:02:01,920 --> 00:02:04,000
Once you've worked out that playing around

40
00:02:04,001 --> 00:02:06,680
with the texture of a
food, making it softer,

41
00:02:06,681 --> 00:02:09,840
tricks that normal satiety
or fullness mechanism,

42
00:02:09,841 --> 00:02:13,840
clearly there's an opportunity there
for some kind of scurrilous behaviour

43
00:02:13,841 --> 00:02:17,440
in making food softer so
that people will eat more,

44
00:02:17,441 --> 00:02:20,040
and therefore you sell
more of your product.

45
00:02:25,320 --> 00:02:29,560
So much of the packaged food
that we eat is incredibly soft.

46
00:02:34,400 --> 00:02:35,440
My kids love these.

47
00:02:37,960 --> 00:02:42,227
You don't typically think of
this as being a soft food because

48
00:02:42,228 --> 00:02:44,680
it's a bit crunchy, but
actually after that initial crunch,

49
00:02:44,681 --> 00:02:46,000
you can just crush it
with your tongue, right?

50
00:02:46,001 --> 00:02:48,240
It's got no resistance at all.

51
00:02:48,241 --> 00:02:50,600
But in terms of the calories per gram,

52
00:02:50,601 --> 00:02:54,480
it's got way more calories
than even a very fatty burger.

53
00:02:54,481 --> 00:02:59,000
So the softness and the energy density mean
that you consume it incredibly quickly.

54
00:02:59,001 --> 00:03:00,720
And there's a food industry term

55
00:03:00,721 --> 00:03:05,120
for these very light, puffy
foods that melt in the mouth.

56
00:03:05,121 --> 00:03:07,880
It's called vanishing caloric density.

57
00:03:11,640 --> 00:03:12,640
Gone.

58
00:03:15,600 --> 00:03:19,840
The thing that makes us eat a lot
isn't just what we do to the food.

59
00:03:21,280 --> 00:03:26,080
It's also about logos, marketing, branding,

60
00:03:26,081 --> 00:03:29,080
and understanding the
box the food comes in.

61
00:03:35,360 --> 00:03:39,080
Eating is a multisensory experience.

62
00:03:39,081 --> 00:03:40,600
There's the look of the food.

63
00:03:40,601 --> 00:03:42,480
There's the smell of the food.

64
00:03:42,481 --> 00:03:46,240
There's the feeling of
the food on your fingers.

65
00:03:46,241 --> 00:03:48,000
Even the sound of food matters.

66
00:03:53,160 --> 00:03:55,720
When you open a fizzy
soda, you've got two things.

67
00:03:55,721 --> 00:03:56,920
Two noises.

68
00:03:56,921 --> 00:04:00,520
You've got the click and the tear.

69
00:04:00,521 --> 00:04:06,200
Sound engineers and manufacturers work
really hard to get that sound just right.

70
00:04:06,201 --> 00:04:07,880
And that's sonic branding.

71
00:04:13,720 --> 00:04:17,480
Many companies have asked me
to work on sonic branding for them.

72
00:04:17,481 --> 00:04:20,480
And I think I can mention
when I was working with Kellogg,

73
00:04:20,481 --> 00:04:23,080
they said, "Ooh,
what's sonic branding?

74
00:04:23,081 --> 00:04:24,914
" And I said,
"You invented this.

75
00:04:24,915 --> 00:04:29,400
" Most people will
remember as children

76
00:04:29,401 --> 00:04:33,320
the experience of
lifting a bowl to their ear.

77
00:04:33,321 --> 00:04:35,360
And what are they listening for?

78
00:04:35,361 --> 00:04:37,760
Snap, crackle, and pop.

79
00:04:37,761 --> 00:04:39,800
That's sonic branding at its best.

80
00:04:39,801 --> 00:04:41,400
And that's the original.

81
00:04:42,960 --> 00:04:44,720
There's a lot of competition out there.

82
00:04:44,721 --> 00:04:49,480
And food companies make their money by the
amount of products we consume from them.

83
00:04:49,481 --> 00:04:52,560
So there's a stomach share
that they're fighting for.

84
00:04:52,561 --> 00:04:57,000
And there are hours in the day, in
between breakfast, lunch, and dinner.

85
00:04:57,001 --> 00:04:58,600
What happens between those hours?

86
00:04:58,601 --> 00:04:59,960
They want us to snack.

87
00:05:02,640 --> 00:05:04,400
You wake up and this is what you have.

88
00:05:04,401 --> 00:05:05,720
Snack number one.

89
00:05:05,721 --> 00:05:06,760
Breakfast shake.

90
00:05:06,761 --> 00:05:08,640
Ultra processed.

91
00:05:08,641 --> 00:05:11,120
This is heavily marketed
for you to have on the go.

92
00:05:11,121 --> 00:05:12,080
Do not sit down.

93
00:05:12,081 --> 00:05:15,600
Do not take time to
crunch through something.

94
00:05:15,601 --> 00:05:17,960
Snack number two of the day.

95
00:05:19,520 --> 00:05:21,000
It's empty calories.

96
00:05:21,001 --> 00:05:22,920
Energy dense, nutrient poor.

97
00:05:23,920 --> 00:05:26,280
Every day, you're starting
to get a little bit peckish.

98
00:05:26,281 --> 00:05:28,040
And what do you have?

99
00:05:28,041 --> 00:05:29,920
Veggie straws.

100
00:05:29,921 --> 00:05:32,960
This is a good example of a
health claim snacking product.

101
00:05:32,961 --> 00:05:36,840
Whereas before we would
have had food, actual food,

102
00:05:36,841 --> 00:05:41,720
now we are marketed into believing that
this is actually a healthy replacement.

103
00:05:43,560 --> 00:05:48,040
Some snacking products have now been made
to be linked with being physically active.

104
00:05:48,041 --> 00:05:53,040
So after the gym, I have a
high protein, low sugar bar.

105
00:05:53,560 --> 00:05:55,640
Instead of having a healthier option.

106
00:05:57,400 --> 00:06:00,197
You finish having dinner
and you have these

107
00:06:00,198 --> 00:06:03,600
snacks that are sold
to you as more to share.

108
00:06:03,601 --> 00:06:08,120
Where in fact, you can just finish
them watching the TV by yourself.

109
00:06:08,121 --> 00:06:09,880
I do like them.

110
00:06:09,881 --> 00:06:11,320
I cannot stop eating them.

111
00:06:14,720 --> 00:06:15,840
And I literally can't.

112
00:06:15,841 --> 00:06:18,320
Oh my God.

113
00:06:18,321 --> 00:06:21,200
I think one of the biggest
problems with this kind of food

114
00:06:21,201 --> 00:06:23,200
is that so many of us
struggle to stop eating them.

115
00:06:23,201 --> 00:06:25,320
Hi everyone.

116
00:06:25,321 --> 00:06:28,034
I'm so thrilled to be
here today to speak with

117
00:06:28,035 --> 00:06:30,840
you on my research
that looks at parallels

118
00:06:30,841 --> 00:06:35,000
between addictive substances
and ultra processed food.

119
00:06:35,001 --> 00:06:36,480
When we look at the sorts of foods

120
00:06:36,481 --> 00:06:39,403
that trigger those key
diagnostic indicators

121
00:06:39,404 --> 00:06:42,240
of addiction, it's really
clear what it's not.

122
00:06:42,241 --> 00:06:46,168
It's not minimally
processed foods like fruits or

123
00:06:46,169 --> 00:06:50,560
vegetables or beans or lean
meats like chicken breast.

124
00:06:50,561 --> 00:06:52,840
It's really processed foods.

125
00:06:52,841 --> 00:06:54,120
It's chocolate.

126
00:06:54,121 --> 00:06:55,240
It's ice cream.

127
00:06:55,241 --> 00:06:56,640
It's pizza.

128
00:06:56,641 --> 00:06:58,600
It's foods that don't exist in nature.

129
00:07:00,960 --> 00:07:04,270
The potency and the
reward power of these ultra

130
00:07:04,271 --> 00:07:07,880
processed foods can
trigger an addictive response

131
00:07:07,881 --> 00:07:11,800
that leads them to consume
these in such a compulsive way

132
00:07:11,801 --> 00:07:13,795
that even if they want
to cut down, even if they

133
00:07:13,796 --> 00:07:17,320
know it's killing them,
they find they can't stop.

134
00:07:17,321 --> 00:07:22,480
Imagine you're trying to cut down on ultra
processed food or avoid it altogether.

135
00:07:22,481 --> 00:07:27,680
For a start, it might be the
only food you can afford.

136
00:07:27,681 --> 00:07:30,720
And that is true for millions of people.

137
00:07:30,721 --> 00:07:32,880
But it's everywhere.

138
00:07:32,881 --> 00:07:35,040
And it's engineered and then marketed

139
00:07:35,041 --> 00:07:39,880
by some of the smartest
people on Earth to be irresistible.

140
00:07:42,640 --> 00:07:44,640
So if someone is watching
this and they are struggling

141
00:07:44,641 --> 00:07:46,920
with their weight, with
diet related disease,

142
00:07:46,921 --> 00:07:50,160
I just want to reach out and grab
them and go, this is not your fault.

143
00:07:50,161 --> 00:07:51,440
It is not you.

144
00:07:51,441 --> 00:07:52,120
It is the food.

145
00:07:52,121 --> 00:07:53,240
It is the food.

146
00:07:55,840 --> 00:07:57,553
The Food and Drink
Federation declined our request

147
00:07:57,554 --> 00:08:00,440
for an interview but
provided this statement.

148
00:08:00,441 --> 00:08:03,440
Food and drink manufacturers take
the issue of obesity and poor diets

149
00:08:03,441 --> 00:08:05,363
very seriously, and we
know we have a key role

150
00:08:05,364 --> 00:08:08,200
to play in helping people
to eat balanced diets.

151
00:08:08,201 --> 00:08:10,720
Our members continue to invest
hundreds of millions in pounds

152
00:08:10,721 --> 00:08:13,080
in creating healthier
products for shoppers.

153
00:08:13,081 --> 00:08:16,520
As a result, UK shopping baskets
now contain significantly less salt,

154
00:08:16,521 --> 00:08:19,160
sugar and calories than
they did a decade ago.

155
00:08:19,161 --> 00:08:20,331
Companies are also
working to raise the fibre,

156
00:08:20,332 --> 00:08:23,840
fruit and vegetable
content, of their products.

157
00:08:23,841 --> 00:08:25,260
It's of course up to
government if they want

158
00:08:25,261 --> 00:08:27,720
to introduce new
taxes or warning labels.

159
00:08:27,721 --> 00:08:29,800
However, taxes will
push up the cost of food

160
00:08:29,801 --> 00:08:33,280
and could disincentivise ongoing
investment in healthier products.

161
00:08:33,281 --> 00:08:36,960
We think there are more effective ways
to encourage positive dietary change.

162
00:08:36,961 --> 00:08:39,600
On labelling, we believe
the UK's traffic light system

163
00:08:39,601 --> 00:08:42,880
is a more positive way of nudging
consumers towards healthier choices

164
00:08:42,881 --> 00:08:45,047
than warning labels,
where global evidence

165
00:08:45,048 --> 00:08:47,840
suggests the longer
term impact is limited.

166
00:08:47,841 --> 00:08:51,400
However, we would support a labelling
review, including to test whether consistent,

167
00:08:51,401 --> 00:08:55,560
positive labelling on all healthier
products would help consumers.

168
00:08:55,561 --> 00:08:58,360
The government's Scientific
Advisory Committee on Nutrition

169
00:08:58,361 --> 00:09:00,104
had said there's
insufficient scientific

170
00:09:00,105 --> 00:09:02,920
evidence on the concept
of ultra-processed foods

171
00:09:02,921 --> 00:09:05,374
for it to be used for
dietary guidance or policy

172
00:09:05,375 --> 00:09:07,920
making, and that further
research is needed.

173
00:09:07,921 --> 00:09:10,920
If research comes to light that
processing is a cause for concern,

174
00:09:10,921 --> 00:09:14,440
the food industry will act quickly to
change their ingredients or processes.

175
00:09:43,380 --> 00:09:51,380
Thank you.

